HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1137
By Keisling
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Geneva Bartlett of
Celina.
WHEREAS, it was with great sadness that the members of this General Assembly
learned of the passing of Geneva Bartlett, who will be fondly remembered as a beloved wife,
mother, grandmother, influencer, teacher of generations, and friend; and
WHEREAS, a child of the Great Depression, Geneva Andrews was born in the Free Hills
community of Celina in Clay County, which was established in 1816 as one of the first African-
American communities of Freedmen in the South; and
WHEREAS, Geneva Andrews Bartlett was heavily influenced by her lineage as a
descendant of the first settlers of the aptly named Free Hills, and her proud heritage inspired her
to live in the form and function of communal responsibility; and
WHEREAS, as a child, Mrs. Bartlett attended the segregated Free Hills School in her
community; at this small, two-room schoolhouse, she prepared herself for an expansive world of
education, pride, and activism that would quietly intersect with legends both at home and
abroad; and
WHEREAS, after graduating from Darwin High School, Mrs. Bartlett enrolled at
Tennessee A&I State University (now Tennessee State University), where she pursued a
bachelor's degree in business education and sang in the choir; she made money to support her
education by babysitting for the children of Nashville's West political family, including future
Nashville Mayor Ben West; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Bartlett graduated from Tennessee A&I in 1961, and armed with her
degree and the spirit of a teacher, she returned to Free Hills School to begin her teaching
HJR1137
015673
- 1 -

career, serving as the only teacher of grades one through eight at her alma mater until the
integration of schools in Clay County in 1963; and
WHEREAS, having eagerly awaited the promise of equality via integration, Mrs. Bartlett
was greatly disappointed to discover that she had been assigned the role of secretary in the
newly integrated school system; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Bartlett possessed the fiery spirit for which her family was renowned
and refused to accept this slight; instead, she successfully sought intervention that assured she
would continue her career in a classroom setting; and
WHEREAS, teaching in Clay County schools for forty-one total years, with thirty-nine of
those years being in an integrated setting, Mrs. Bartlett molded thousands of minds as a
business education teacher, treasured librarian, and eventually, a Title I teacher at Celina K-8;
and
WHEREAS, on Christmas Day 1962, Geneva Andrews wed her childhood sweetheart
and the love of her life, Bobby Bartlett, in the church of their membership since birth, Free Hills
Church of Christ; the couple was blessed with two daughters, Angela and Anita, who took after
their mother as dedicated students and their father as student athletes; and
WHEREAS, she joined Sigma Gamma Rho Sorority, Incorporated, in 1960, and her
daughters later followed in her footsteps as members of the sorority; Mrs. Bartlett was a
member of the Kappa Tau Sigma Alumni Chapter of Sigma Gamma Rho at the time of her
passing; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Bartlett also held memberships in the Home Demonstration Club, the
Tennessee Education Association, and the National Education Association; and
WHEREAS, later in life, Geneva Bartlett continued to excel as a mother, "Nana," friend,
aunt, cousin, and church member, singing enthusiastically at worship services; and
- 2 - 015673

WHEREAS, Geneva Andrews Bartlett is survived by her loving husband of sixty-four
years, Bobby Bartlett; daughters, Angela Bartlett and Anita (Darnell) Spann; grandchildren,
Maidra Treece, Hillery Treece, Jameson Spann, and Jordan Spann; and siblings, Ann Hill
Jackson, John "Sonny" Graves, Robert "Junebugg" Garrett, Jr., Connie Garrett, and Denise
Andrews; and
WHEREAS, she was preceded in death by her parents, Ollie Mai Andrews Wilson
Hamilton and Robert "Bud" Garrett, Sr., and siblings, Bea Audrey Isabel, Jack Andrews, and
Austin Bailey; and
WHEREAS, Geneva Bartlett is deeply mourned by her loving family and her friends and
neighbors in Celina, and we wish to pay our respects to a gracious lady who lived the examined
life of the mind and soul while serving others with her big heart; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we celebrate the life of Geneva Bartlett, even as we honor her memory
and mourn her passing, remembering her life of purpose and commitment to education and
mentorship.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
